items.title: Black smoke emerges at Vatican as conclave fails to elect pope - as it happened
items.snippet: On May 7, 2025, the Vatican began the conclave to select a new pope following the death of Pope Francis last month at the age of 88. The first day concluded without an election, as signaled by the emergence of black smoke from the Sistine Chapel chimney at 9:05pm local time. This outcome aligns with expectations, since papal selection rarely occurs on the first day. A total of 133 cardinal electors, mostly appointed by Pope Francis, are participating in the conclave. The process began with a Mass and formal procession into the Sistine Chapel, where the cardinals took an oath of secrecy and surrendered their phones. One round of voting took place today, and up to four more are expected tomorrow—two in the morning and two in the afternoon. The next pope will inherit a challenging agenda, including issues related to church unity, international diplomacy, governance, financial oversight, and inclusion of women. Various candidates with differing theological perspectives are being considered, but a successor has yet to be chosen. The conclave will continue until a candidate secures the required two-thirds majority, or 89 votes.

parts:
iturn0image0turn0image1turn0image3turn0image4The noticeable presence of priests in Rome is due to the ongoing papal conclave, convened to elect a successor to Pope Francis, who passed away on April 21, 2025. citeturn0news21

While only the 133 cardinal electors participate in the voting process within the Sistine Chapel, many other clergy members have traveled to Rome for various reasons:

- **Liturgical Participation**: Priests are involved in special Masses and prayer services associated with the conclave, including the "Missa pro eligendo Romano Pontifice" celebrated before the conclave's commencement. citeturn0search0

- **Spiritual Support**: They offer spiritual guidance and sacraments to the multitude of pilgrims and faithful gathered in the city during this significant period.

- **Media and Communication**: Some priests serve as spokespersons or commentators for media outlets, providing insights into the conclave's proceedings and the Church's future direction.

- **Institutional Duties**: Clergy affiliated with various Vatican departments or religious orders may have responsibilities related to the conclave or the Church's operations during the sede vacante period.

Their presence underscores the global significance of the papal election and the unity of the Church during this pivotal moment.

items.title: No new pope elected yet after black smoke pours out of Sistine Chapel's chimney
items.snippet: As of Thursday morning, cardinals at the Vatican have not elected a new pope to succeed Pope Francis, with black smoke signaling inconclusive results from the Sistine Chapel chimney following two additional rounds of voting. The required two-thirds majority, or 89 votes, has not been achieved among the 133 eligible cardinals. The conclave, a centuries-old and highly secretive process, may continue into the afternoon with hopes for a decision. Cardinal Pietro Parolin, the church’s secretary of state and a leading contender, is playing a prominent role in the proceedings. The conclave began Wednesday afternoon and has attracted global attention, with pilgrims, journalists, and observers gathering at St. Peter’s Square, watching for the telltale white smoke that will announce the election of the 267th pope. Historical precedent suggests the process might require several ballots, as with recent popes. Popular opinions from the square reflect admiration for Pope Francis' outreach while expressing hopes for a leader who can further reform efforts. One favored candidate is Cardinal Pierbattista Pizzaballa, the Latin Patriarch of Jerusalem. Voting follows a meticulous ritual, with ballots read, tallied, and ceremonially burned to produce either white or black smoke to convey the outcome.

parts: What’s the relationship btwn boticelli and da Vinci

Sandro Botticelli and Leonardo da Vinci were both prominent artists of the Italian Renaissance, active during the late 15th century, and although they were contemporaries and both worked in Florence, their relationship was more contextual than personal.

**Key points of connection and contrast:**

- **Florentine School**: Both were part of the Florentine artistic scene and influenced by the innovations of the time, especially those of their teacher or mentors. Botticelli was influenced by Filippo Lippi and later the Neoplatonic thinkers at the Medici court, while Leonardo trained under Andrea del Verrocchio.

- **Medici Patronage**: Both benefited from the patronage of the powerful Medici family, which fostered a vibrant cultural environment that brought artists into overlapping circles.

- **Style and Philosophy**: Botticelli’s work is characterized by lyrical, linear grace and mythological or religious themes, often symbolic and idealized (e.g. *The Birth of Venus*). Leonardo, in contrast, focused on realism, anatomical accuracy, and scientific inquiry (e.g. *The Last Supper*, *Vitruvian Man*).

- **Interaction**: There is no strong evidence they collaborated or had a close personal relationship, but they would certainly have been aware of each other’s work. Botticelli even contributed to the decoration of the Sistine Chapel alongside other artists including a young Perugino, who later influenced Raphael—another tie in the Renaissance web that included da Vinci.
